'''Kao Ping-tse''' ({{zh|c=高平子}}; 23 December 1888 - 23 March 1970) was a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] [[astronomy|astronomer]]. He was entirely self-taught in this field.{{citation needed|date=October 2009}} The crater [[Kao (crater)|Kao]] on the [[Moon]] is named in his honor.
Kao was born in [[Shanghai]]. His father was a revolutionary, a [[Imperial examination#juren|Jǔrén 舉人]], and a key figure of the ''Nan Society'' (''South Society'', [[:zh:南社|南社]]) in the late [[Qing Dynasty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nanshewan.b121.53dns.com/suzhi/jnhxsl.txt |title=参加南社纪念会姓氏录 List of Nan Society member |publisher=南社研究網 Research of Nan Society |accessdate=2009-10-08 |language=zh |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121184213/http://nanshewan.b121.53dns.com/suzhi/jnhxsl.txt |archivedate=November 21, 2008 |df= }} The Wayback Machine's might be helpful, but it appears as a mess of eight-bit characters.</ref> He worked at [[Qingdao]] Observatory, received from the Japanese after the [[Washington Naval Conference]] in 1924. He then worked at the [[Academia Sinica]] Institute of Astronomy & Astrophysics, one of the founders of [[Purple Mountain Observatory]].
During World War II, he lived in Shanghai. He moved to [[Taiwan]] in 1948, during the [[Chinese Civil War]]. He died in [[Taipei]].
