[[File:chemfm peroxodicarbonate 2neg.svg|141px|right]]<!--Placeholder for a proper diagram--> In [[chemistry]], '''peroxydicarbonate''' (sometimes '''peroxodicarbonate''') is a [[valence (chemistry)|divalent]] [[anion]] with formula {{chem|C|2|O|6|2−}}. It is one of the [[oxocarbon anion]]s, which consist solely of [[carbon]] and [[oxygen]]. Its molecular structure can be viewed as two [[carbonate]] anions joined so as to form a [[peroxide]] bridge –O–O–.
The anion is formed, together with [[peroxocarbonate]] {{chem|C|O|4|2−}}, at the negative [[electrode]] during [[electrolysis]] of molten [[lithium carbonate]].<ref name="chen">{{cite journal |doi= 10.1021/jp035749l |pages= 7553–7556 |title= First Spectroscopic Observation of Peroxocarbonate/ Peroxodicarbonate in Molten Carbonate |year= 2004 |last1= Chen |first1= Li-Jiang |last2= Lin |first2= Chang-Jian |last3= Zuo |first3= Juan |last4= Song |first4= Ling-Chun |last5= Huang |first5= Chao-Ming |journal= The Journal of Physical Chemistry B |volume= 108 |issue= 23}}</ref> The anion can also be obtained by electrolysis of a saturated solution of rubidium carbonate in water.<ref name=dinnebier3/>
[[Potassium peroxydicarbonate]] K<sub>2</sub>C<sub>2</sub>O<sub>6</sub> was obtained by [[E. J. Constam|Constam]] and [[A. von Hansen|von Hansen]] in 1895;<ref name=Constam>{{cite journal |first1= E. J. |last1= Constam |first2= A. |last2= von Hansen |year= 1895 |journal= Zeitschrift für Elektrochemie |volume= 7}}</ref> its crystal structure was determined only in 2002.<ref name=dinnebier2>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1002/1521-3773(20020603)41:11<1922::AID-ANIE1922>3.0.CO;2-T |pages= 1922–1924 |title= Crystal Structure of K<sub>2</sub>[C<sub>2</sub>O<sub>6</sub>] |year= 2002 |last1= Dinnebier |first1= Robert E. |last2= Vensky |first2= Sascha |last3= Stephens |first3= Peter W. |last4= Jansen |first4= Martin |journal= Angewandte Chemie International Edition |volume= 41 |issue= 11}}</ref> It too can be obtained by electrolysis of a saturated potassium carbonate solution at −20&nbsp;°C. It is a light blue crystalline solid that decomposes at 141&nbsp;°C, releasing [[oxygen]] and carbon dioxide, and decomposes slowly at lower temperatures.<ref name=dinnebier2/>
[[Rubidium peroxodicarbonate]] is a light blue crystalline solid that decomposes at 424 K. Its structure was published in 2003.<ref name=dinnebier3>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1002/chem.200304914 |pages= 4391–4395 |title= Crystal and Molecular Structure of Rubidium Peroxodicarbonate Rb<sub>2</sub>[C<sub>2</sub>O<sub>6</sub>] |year= 2003 |last1= Dinnebier |first1= Robert E. |last2= Vensky |first2= Sascha |last3= Jansen |first3= Martin |journal= Chemistry: A European Journal |volume= 9 |pmid= 14502625 |issue= 18}}</ref> In both salts, each of the two carbonate units is planar. In the [[rubidium]] salt the whole molecule is planar, whereas in the [[potassium]] salt the two units lie on different and nearly perpendicular planes, both of which contain the O–O bond.<ref name=dinnebier3/>
==See also== *[[Dicarbonate]] *[[Sodium percarbonate]]
