'''Sir Wilfrid Russell Grimwade''' (15 October 1879 - 2 November 1955) was an Australian chemist, botanist, industrialist and philanthropist. He was the son of [[Frederick Sheppard Grimwade]] and brother of [[Harold Grimwade]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article240011644 |title=The Grimwades of Melbourne |newspaper=[[Smith's Weekly]] |volume=XXVIII, |issue=38 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=16 November 1946 |accessdate=16 August 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

An endowment by Grimwald in 1929 was used to create the Russell Grimwade Prize, a scholarship for study of forestry. As of 2018, the annual prize value is $40,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article997221 |title=FORESTRY |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=3, |issue=419 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=13 February 1929 |accessdate=16 August 2018 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fwpa.com.au/14-scholarships-and-prizes/3-russell-grimwade-prize-worth-40-000.html | publisher=Forest and Wood Products Australia | title=Russell Grimwade Prize worth $40,000}}</ref> In 1934, he presented [[Cooks' Cottage]] to Victoria after purchasing it in England and shipping it to Australia.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article35011609 |title=CAPTAIN COOK'S' COTTAGE HANDED OVER |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=16 October 1934 |accessdate=16 August 2018 |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

He received a CBE in 1935 and was knighted in 1950.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71777817 |title=He 'melted' the air... |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)]] |location=Victoria, Australia |date=3 November 1955 |accessdate=16 August 2018 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article99098744 |title=AUSTRALIANS WHO WERE KNIGHTED |newspaper=[[The Northern Star|Northern Star]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=8 June 1950 |accessdate=16 August 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

